Visual Data Story – Device Usage Observations

Most Observed Devices

The bar chart shows the number of device types that were observed in public areas during the data collection period. Smartphones are the most common devices followed by laptops and tablets. This visualization helps us understand which digital devices dominate everyday public use. —

Usage Duration by Age Group

The density plot shows the estimated device usage duration for three age groups which include Youth, Adults and Seniors.
The younger population demonstrates both longer usage times and wider distribution while older groups display shorter and more uniform usage periods.
The plot demonstrates how age affects the level of digital engagement. —

Device Use Over Time

The time series chart shows the complete device usage data collected throughout the observation period.
The device usage shows noticeable peaks which occur on weekends and public holidays indicating that people use devices more during their free time.
This gives a temporal view of digital behavior across time.

This chart explores the character length of the device labels recorded during observation.
Most of the device names, such as “phone”, “laptop”, or “tablet”, are relatively short, while a few outliers include slightly longer terms.
The visualization uses str_length() from the stringr package and contributes to our analysis by highlighting how concise or varied the naming of device types can be in real-world logging situations. —

Summary of Observed Data

The visual data story draws its information from structured observational data that researchers collected through Google Forms during multiple days.
The dataset contains actual observations of public space digital device usage which each row represents.
The dataset contains four variables which include device type and age group and usage duration in minutes and posture and time of day.

The primary objective of this project involves studying human interactions with digital devices through time-based and demographic and environmental factors.
The three core visualizations show the most observed devices and usage duration differences by age group and daily trends throughout the day.
A fourth visualization examines the length of device labels through string manipulation functions such as str_length which was introduced in Lab 4.
The final chart introduces linguistic elements to the dataset to show both the general patterns and specific variations in device logging.

The visualizations were created with R and {ggplot2} before being integrated into an HTML-based story that uses CSS for visual presentation and accessibility purposes.
